    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:2479c1ef-1cb2-4bd9-b06d-19412c2a2a1c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 38-year-old male with a medium build and a slightly sallow complexion, reflecting his recent struggles with liver inflammation. He stands 178 cm tall and weighs 81 kg. Over the past several months, he has noticed increasing fatigue that interrupts his daily routine, a persistent dull ache in his right upper abdomen, and intermittent episodes of nausea following meals. He has also observed that his urine has taken on a darker, amber hue, and colleagues have remarked that his eyes appear slightly yellow-tinged — signs that alarmed him and prompted his visit to the gastroenterology clinic.\n\n{patientName} works as a high school geography teacher in a mid-sized city, a job he finds deeply rewarding but mentally taxing. He spends long hours on his feet and often skips lunch due to time constraints. Outside of work, he is an enthusiastic amateur cyclist who typically rides 40–60 km on weekends. Over the last two months, however, fatigue and abdominal discomfort have significantly curtailed his cycling activities, which has been a source of frustration and mild depression.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is outgoing and maintains a close-knit circle of friends. He lives with his long-term partner and their 7-year-old daughter. He drinks alcohol socially — approximately 3–4 standard drinks per week — and denies recreational drug use. He is a non-smoker. His diet has historically been balanced, though he admits to increased reliance on processed convenience foods since his symptoms began, as cooking has felt burdensome.\n\nOn physical examination, he presents with mild icterus (jaundice) of the sclerae, tender hepatomegaly approximately 2 cm below the right costal margin, and mild spider angiomata on the upper chest. There is no ascites or peripheral oedema. He is alert and oriented, though noticeably fatigued in his demeanour and affect."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:f4ea38e0-76bd-478a-a69d-8f762d7b4f40",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior history of chronic liver disease, viral hepatitis, or significant alcohol misuse. Approximately six months ago, he completed a 10-day course of amoxicillin for a dental abscess — a temporally associated exposure noted in his history. He has no history of blood transfusions or intravenous drug use. He underwent an upper gastrointestinal endoscopy three years ago for epigastric discomfort, which was unremarkable. He had an abdominal ultrasound 18 months ago for suspected gallstones; at that time, the liver appeared within normal limits. A liver biopsy was performed during the current diagnostic workup, revealing moderate lobular hepatitis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate and mild portal fibrosis. His BMI is 25.6. He has no known autoimmune conditions, though his rheumatologist has flagged mildly elevated ANA titres warranting follow-up. He takes no regular medications other than those prescribed following this diagnosis. There is a family history of liver disease (paternal uncle) and type 2 diabetes (maternal side). He has no known drug allergies documented until the current episode."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
